so while machines might have 16 installed it is not used.

Realizing that VS 2019 does not work and trying VS 2017 I tried the following from a **Developer Command Prompt for VS 2017**:
```
build.bat --skip_submodule_sync --cmake_path "C:\Program Files\CMake\bin\cmake.exe" --config RelWithDebInfo --build_shared_lib --build_csharp --parallel --cuda_home "C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v10.2" --cudnn_home C:\git\nvidia\cuda --tensorrt_home C:\git\nvidia\TensorRT-6.0.1.5 --use_tensorrt
```
with paths as per my dev machine.  Note that you need to specify cmake path as the cmake bundled with VS 2017 is too old.

This however fails in many places, but specifically `onnxruntime` project fails due to an unnecessary delayload:
```
LINK : warning LNK4199: /DELAYLOAD:cudart64_102.dll ignored; no imports found from cudart64_102.dll [C:\git\oss\onnxruntime\build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\onn
xruntime.vcxproj]
LINK : error LNK1218: warning treated as error; no output file generated [C:\git\oss\onnxruntime\build\Windows\RelWithDebInfo\onnxruntime.vcxproj]
```
removing this delay load finally meant I got a `onnxruntime.dll`, however there are lots of build errors in test projects e.g. `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Tests` fails.
Should change the delay load to be for `cudart64_101.dll` instead.

The `Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime` fails for last copying step:
```
3>C:\Program Files (x86)\Microsoft Visual Studio\2017\Professional\MSBuild\15.0\Bin\Microsoft.Common.CurrentVersion.targets(4582,5): error MSB3030: Could not copy the file "C:\git\oss\onnxruntime\build\Windows\Release\Release\onnxruntime.dll" because it was not found.
```
because it does not user the proper configuration which is `RelWithDebInfo` not `Release`.

@snnn @stevenlix I finally managed to build this after updating to 1d79926d273d01817ce93f001f36f417ab05f8a0 with the following build parameters:
```
build.bat  --cmake_path "C:\Program Files\CMake\bin\cmake.exe" --config RelWithDebInfo --build_shared_lib --build_csharp --parallel --use_cuda --cuda_version 10.2 --cuda_home "C:\Program Files\NVIDIA GPU Computing Toolkit\CUDA\v10.2" --cudnn_home C:\git\nvidia\cuda --use_tensorrt --tensorrt_home C:\git\nvidia\TensorRT-7.0.0.11 --use_dnnl --cmake_generator "Visual Studio 16 2019" --skip_tests
```
Run from a **Developer Command Prompt for VS 2019**. I am, therefore, closing the issue.
